    {
      "id": "971111698f52770106e25970998e8df4a7fa2e93",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2015-08-06 15:38:14.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1\n\nAnn, those warnings were generated because this patch is based on a parent that is almost a month old, but are harmless at this point. \n\nThe patch looks OK, but my preference would be to use the kernel percpu_counter functionality rather than overloading the stats functionality to handle this.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "3a6e891317f47e0e5f8658a776d0fbb8340329b5",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 358,
        "name": "Ann Koehler",
        "email": "amk@cray.com",
        "username": "amk",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2015-08-06 16:28:56.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nAh, I misunderstood what you meant by percpu_counters in your PS1 comment. I agree using the kernel percpu_counter is cleaner. I assume since you gave PS2 a +1 that Intel will pick up the patch as is. I'll plan to submit a cleanup patch when my schedule allows.\n\nFYI, we found that this patch also fixed a serious problem of CPU stalls with SLES12. Nearly every system test run hit several stalls along the try_to_free_pages path. lu_cache_shrink was in most of the stack traces, often waiting in osq_lock for the lu_sites_guard lock.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
